  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do my family and I Live in tijuana for one month?",
  "response": "Living in Tijuana for a month can be an exciting and affordable experience for you and your family. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you plan your stay:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Research and Planning**\n- **Visa Requirements**: Check if you need a visa to stay in Mexico for a month. Many countries, including the U.S. and Canada, allow visa-free stays for up to 180 days for tourism purposes.\n- **Health Insurance**: Ensure you and your family have travel or international health insurance that covers you in Mexico.\n- **Budget**: Tijuana is relatively affordable, but plan your budget for accommodation, food, transportation, and activities.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Accommodation**\n- **Short-Term Rentals**: Look for furnished apartments or houses on platforms like Airbnb, Vrbo, or local rental websites.\n- **Hotels or Extended Stays**: Some hotels offer monthly rates for long-term stays.\n- **Neighborhoods**: Consider safe and family-friendly areas like Zona R\u00edo, Playas de Tijuana, or Chapultepec.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Transportation**\n- **Walkability**: Choose a neighborhood where you can walk to grocery stores, parks, and restaurants.\n- **Public Transit**: Tijuana has buses and taxis, but rideshare apps like Uber or DiDi are safer and more convenient.\n- **Driving**: If you plan to drive, ensure your vehicle insurance is valid in Mexico, or rent a car locally.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Food and Groceries**\n- **Local Markets**: Visit Mercado Hidalgo or other local markets for fresh produce and authentic Mexican ingredients.\n- **Supermarkets**: Chains like Soriana, Calimax, or Walmart offer familiar grocery options.\n- **Dining Out**: Tijuana has excellent and affordable restaurants. Try street food, tacos, and seafood.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Communication**\n- **SIM Cards**: Purchase a local SIM card for your phone for affordable data and calls. Companies like Telcel, Movistar, or AT&T Mexico offer prepaid plans.\n- **Wi-Fi**: Most short-term rentals and hotels will have Wi-Fi, but check the speed and reliability.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Safety**\n- **Stay Informed**: Research safe areas and avoid risky neighborhoods, especially at night.\n- **Emergency Numbers**: Save local emergency numbers (911 in Mexico works for police, fire, and medical emergencies).\n- **Health Precautions**: Drink bottled water and avoid risky street food if you\u2019re not accustomed to it.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Activities and Entertainment**\n- **Parks and Beaches**: Visit Parque Morelos, Parque de la Amistad, or Playas de Tijuana.\n- **Cultural Sites**: Explore Centro Cultural Tijuana, Pasaje Rodr\u00edguez, or the Tijuana Arch.\n- **Day Trips**: Take a trip to nearby Rosarito, Ensenada, or Tecate.\n\n---\n\n### **8. Finances**\n- **Currency**: Use Mexican pesos for most transactions. ATMs are widely available for cash withdrawals.\n- **Credit Cards**: Most businesses accept credit cards, but smaller vendors may prefer cash.\n\n---\n\n### **9. Documentation**\n- **Passports**: Ensure all family members have valid passports.\n- **Immigration Form**: You\u2019ll receive an FMM (Forma Migratoria M\u00faltiple) upon entry. Keep it safe and return it when you leave.\n\n---\n\n### **10. Prepare for Culture and Language**\n- **Spanish**: Learn some basic Spanish phrases, though many locals speak English, especially in tourist areas.\n- **Etiquette**: Familiarize yourself with Mexican customs and local traditions.\n\n---\n\nBy planning ahead and staying organized, you and your family can enjoy a comfortable and memorable month in Tijuana!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
